he American and international Jewish community with distinction in his roles as a synagogue rabbi, university professor, and public intellectual. These articles, like the honoree, recognize the importance of both history and memory, emphasize the necessity of accuracy in historiography, and do not shy away from inconvenient truths. They are divided into three categories that help frame the discussion around “facing the truths of history”: Textual Traditions, Memory and Making of Meaning, and (Re)Creating a Usable Past. The volume also includes a brief sketch of Schacter’s life and work and a bibliography of his publications.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJewsxHistoriography. 0aJewsxHistory. 0aJudaismxHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aBible, Talmud, Jewish law, Ecumenism, American Judaism, COVID-19, Holocaust, Feminist literary critique, Jewish historiography, History and memory.1 aBarack Fishman, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaumel-Schwartz, Judith Tydor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerman, Ari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Menachem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlebach, Elisheva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubin, Lois C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEleff , Zev, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEleff, Zev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllenson, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerziger, Adam S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat